<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-444-966  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 444 966.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Publishing Systems  April 23 1990 v19 n15p44(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Canadian firm offers Waterloo software; PAT fast retrieval engineis first product from Canadian University. (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Open Text Systems (product introduction).andO;Product:   PAT (Search software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware PackagesDocument Management SystemsSearching.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Canadian firm offers Waterloo software A new Canadian software firm, OpenText Systems, has been formed to market the software developed by theUniversity of Waterloo's Centre for the New Oxford English Dictionary.andP;  TheCentre was part of the team that published the 2nd edition of the OED inApril 1989 and developed a retrieval engine to accompany it.andP;  It is nowoffering the retrieval engine to academic and commercial customers.andM;The retrieval system, called PAT, was designed for speed on large documents.andO;Open Text claims PAT is as fast as any hardware-assisted retrieval engine onthe market.andP;  Its benchmark is a search on an arbitrary text string in the OED(roughly 400 MB of text), which takes PAT less than one second on a Sun3/160.andM;Like other full-text engines, PAT preprocesses an index of the database.andP;  Itsindex points may be as fine as every character or, through the use ofuser-modifiable rules, at every word.andP;  Proximity, boolean and set-algebraicsearch operations are standard, as in most retrieval systems.andP;  In addition,though, PAT's index supports tagging of the text, which enables searches tobe restricted to regions of the database.andP;  Tagging may be generic markup,like SGML, or another database scheme; the regions of the search may bepredefined or selected at run-time as part of the search.andM;Open Text will initially target reference publishers, educationaladministrators and government agencies.andP;  It has already successfully appliedPAT to the OED, the Bible, library records, legislation, bibliographic data,newswire text, Sherlock Holmes stories and its own documentation.andM;PAT is written in C, and Open Text says it will run on any computer with a32-bit address space, a standard C library and the ability to treat files asseekable byte streams in the Unix style.andM;Pricing depends on the number of CPUs involved and whether the software willbe used by commercial or academic users.andP;  For information, contact Tim Brayor David Terry at the following address:andM;Open Text Systems, Unit 622, Waterloo Town Square, Waterloo, Ontario, CanadaN2J 1P2; phone (519) 746-8288.andO;</TEXT></DOC>